About
The Catacombs of Priscilla, sits on the Via Salaria, with its entrance in the convent of the Benedictine Sisters of Priscilla. It is mentioned in all of the most ancient documents on Christian topography and liturgy in Rome; because of the great number of martyrs buried within it, it was called “regina catacumbarum – the queen of the catacombs.” Originally dug out from the second to fifth centuries, it began as a series of underground burial chambers, of which the most important are the “arenarium” or sand-quarry, the cryptoporticus, (an underground area to get away from the summer heat), and the hypogeum with the tombs of the Acilius Glabrio family. The noblewoman Priscilla, who granted the Church use of the property, was a member of this family; her commemoration is noted on January 16th in the Roman Martyrology, which speaks of her as a benefactor of the Christian community in Rome. This cemetery was lost like all the others after the entrances were blocked to protect it from thiev

Interesting, informative tour!
Sep 2024 • Couples
Very interesting visit to the catacombs just outside of the main area of Rome. We are so glad we made this ~15-20 minute ride to the Priscilla Catacombs. The visit was guided by a wonderful nun who led us through the catacombs, explaining the history and various incredible artifacts in the catacombs, including some of the first paintings found of baby Jesus. We were amazed at the vastness of the catacombs and preservation of the structure and artwork within. The tour was informative, interesting, and well paced. The Sister was extremely knowledgeable and explained everything in a very engaging way that was easy to absorb. The tour ran ~45 min to an hour and questions were welcomed! Note, the last tour was around 4:15pm while we were there. Highly recommend!
Written October 15, 2024

352renes
Santa Cruz, CA54 contributions
Worth the effort to visit!
Feb 2024 • Couples
This is the third catacomb that we have visited. Lovely, friendly staff. It was a slow day and we ended up with a private tour in English. Our guide spoke fluent English and was so knowledgeable. This catacomb has some unique early Christian frescos that feature women. The "veiled lady" was particularly beautiful and shows a woman in a ministerial role. This catacomb also has the EARLIEST KNOWN PAINTING OF MARY WITH BABY JESUS--from AD 230! A sweet, simple painting--very different than later paintings with halos and crowns.

I wished that the tour was longer but the vast majority of this catacomb is not open to tourists. There are more than 5 miles of catacombs here!

By the way, the neighborhood was very much a normal, Roman neighborhood, not touristy AT ALL. We enjoyed being away from the tourist crowds and enjoyed the best pizza of our trip at a little local market stand.

We took the Metro and had about a 15-20 minute walk (mostly uphill) through to the Catacomb.
Written March 5, 2024
